body:
Based on the [discourse post](https://yosyshq.discourse.group/t/flops-with-parametrized-aload-arent-optimized-and-synthesis-fails/112).

### Motivation

It seems that the existing dff optimizations don’t detect when ALOAD and AD inputs are driven from the same or complementary signals. This prevents synthesis of designs that contain dffs with parametrized asynchronous reset logic:

```
read_verilog aldffs.v 
proc
hierarchy -check -top top
synth_ice40 -device lp -top top -json top.json

...
4.34. Executing DFFLEGALIZE pass (convert FFs to types supported by the target).
ERROR: FF top.$auto$ff.cc:337:slice$930 (type $_ALDFFE_PNP_) cannot be legalized: dffs with async set and reset are not supported
```

This is the situation after opt (ALOAD polarity is 1’b1 on both):
* $440 has PT1 connected to both ALOAD and AD - equivalent to AD = 1’b1
* $441 has inverted PT1 connected to AD - equivalent to AD = 1’b0

<img width="699" height="817" alt="aldff_inv" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/8d257175-bd2a-47b5-b5a3-cb54379beb0b" />

```verilog
module aload_gdff(...);

   parameter INIT_SOURCE = 1'b1;
   parameter INIT_STATE = 1'b1;
   parameter ASYNC_SOURCE = 1'b1;
   parameter POLARITY = 1'b1;

   input CLK;
   input CE;
   input PT1;
   input PT2;
   input PT3;
   input DIN;
   input SET;
   input RES;
   output wire Q;

   wire	  shared_init;
   assign shared_init = INIT_SOURCE == 1'b1 ? PT1 : PT3;

   wire	  por_init;
   assign por_init = 1'b0 ^ shared_init;

   wire	  async_init;
   assign async_init = ASYNC_SOURCE == 1'b0 ? PT2 : ~ POLARITY;

   wire	  preset;
   assign preset = INIT_STATE == 1'b0 ? por_init : async_init;
   wire	  reset;
   assign reset  = INIT_STATE == 1'b1 ? por_init : async_init;

   wire   aload;
   assign aload = (preset == POLARITY) || (reset == POLARITY);

   wire   ad;
   assign ad = preset == POLARITY;

   always @(posedge CLK, posedge aload) begin
      if (aload)
	Q <= ad;
      else if (CE == 1'b1)
	Q <= DIN;
   end

endmodule // aload_gdff



module top(...);

   input CLK;
   input CE;
   input PT1;
   input PT2;
   input PT3;
   input [3:0] DIN;
   output [3:0]	Q;


   aload_gdff
     #(.INIT_SOURCE(1'b1), .INIT_STATE(1'b0), .ASYNC_SOURCE(1'b1), .POLARITY(1'b1))
   set_1_dff
     (.CLK(CLK), .CE(CE), .PT1(PT1), .PT2(PT2), .PT3(PT3), .DIN(DIN[0]), .Q(Q[0]));

   aload_gdff
     #(.INIT_SOURCE(1'b1), .INIT_STATE(1'b1), .ASYNC_SOURCE(1'b1), .POLARITY(1'b1))
   res_1_dff
     (.CLK(CLK), .CE(CE), .PT1(PT1), .PT2(PT2), .PT3(PT3), .DIN(DIN[1]), .Q(Q[1]));

   aload_gdff
     #(.INIT_SOURCE(1'b1), .INIT_STATE(1'b0), .ASYNC_SOURCE(1'b1), .POLARITY(1'b0))
   set_0_dff
     (.CLK(CLK), .CE(CE), .PT1(PT1), .PT2(PT2), .PT3(PT3), .DIN(DIN[2]), .Q(Q[2]));

   aload_gdff
     #(.INIT_SOURCE(1'b1), .INIT_STATE(1'b1), .ASYNC_SOURCE(1'b1), .POLARITY(1'b0))
   res_0_dff
     (.CLK(CLK), .CE(CE), .PT1(PT1), .PT2(PT2), .PT3(PT3), .DIN(DIN[3]), .Q(Q[3]));

endmodule // top
```

The preset/reset generation is a generic parametrizable implementation:
* INIT_SOURCE controls whether PT1 or PT3 is used for por_init
* ASYNC_SOURCE controls whether PT2 is used or inactive
* INIT_STATE controls whether por_init is used as preset or reset, async_source is used for the "other"

Since ASYNC_SOURCE is 1'b1 for all instances, the above design effectively defines PT1 as either preset or reset, but never both. The 4 instances cover the combinations of INIT_STATE and POLARITY, and logically they should be mapped to $adffe with respective ARST_POLARITY/ARST_VALUE.

As a side note, my original design is in VHDL and GHDL recently changed to generate $aldff* for flops with async set and reset (https://github.com/ghdl/ghdl-yosys-plugin/issues/220).

### Considerations

The same-signal detection is fairly simple. My observation was that redundant/parallel signals are optimized away by opt_expr and the direct signal comparison detects same-signal situations.

For comp-signal detection I initially experimented with programmatically tracing the driver gate and decide based on the logic function whether AD is complement of ALOAD or vice-versa. My design generated only $not or $mux inverters, but I wasn't sure what to expect in general - $nand, $nor etc as well? So I decided to hand this task over to qcsat.
However, the decision to use qcsat could be revised if there's a know set of inverting gates to expect (after opt_expr).

Executing qcsat expects the `-sat` option, a pattern I took over from `run_constbits()`. Thus synthesis needs an intermediate `opt -sat` call to reduce complement situations. Not sure whether `-sat` is mandatory here.

I put the new code into a separate function based on my understanding
* it can't be part of `run()` when using qcsat/modwalker
* it can't be part of `run_constbits()` since this focuses on cell removal and its decision tree doesn't allow me to handle $alddf* (`has_clock` _and_ `has_aload`)

### Tests

The tests exercise the new code for all cell types I'm aware of that contain ALOAD and AD.

